<p>

<b>OPUS</b> is the name of a rechargeable <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../064/6863064.xml">
contactless</link> stored value <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../957/59957.xml">
smart card</link> which is being gradually introduced in most of the  <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../894/23894.xml">
public transit</link> systems in the <region wordnetid="108630039" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../916/5042916.xml">
Canadian</link></region>
 <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../763/75763.xml">
province</link> of <district wordnetid="108552138" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../867/7954867.xml">
Quebec</link></district>
.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref><ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref>  One card can contain up to four different kinds of fares. The main goal behind the creation of this card is to reduce the amount of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../823/10729823.xml">
fare evasion</link> that takes place in the province's transit systems.</p>

